instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands originate from the digital twin controller running on the Raspberry Pi. The controller receives temperature measurements from RabbitMQ, executes a bang‑bang control strategy, and publishes command messages to RabbitMQ to turn the heatbed and fan on or off. Command messages are conveyed over AMQP using a simple payload that indicates actuator state (e.g., 'heatbed: ON', 'fan: OFF'). A safe protocol in the low‑level driver validates incoming commands, ensures they obey safety limits, and confirms execution by publishing status updates back to the broker. The low‑level driver then forwards the validated command to the corresponding actuator and reports execution success or failure. No authentication, encryption, or conflict resolution mechanisms beyond the safety checks are described."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin exchanges information with the physical incubator through an event‑driven message bus (RabbitMQ).  The low‑level driver on the Raspberry Pi periodically reads the two inside temperature sensors and the outside temperature sensor and publishes the readings to a RabbitMQ queue; the controller consumes these messages, drives the fan and heatbed, and publishes its control state back to the same queue.  The temporal granularity of the DT is thus defined by the polling interval of the low‑level driver and by the message round‑trip through RabbitMQ; the exact cycle time is not specified in the documents, but the system is designed to operate within a few seconds per observation cycle."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DT is implemented on a single Raspberry Pi platform and follows a centralized CPS‑centric architecture.  Key components include: 1) the low‑level driver, which abstracts sensor/actuator I/O with a safe protocol and publishes sensor data to RabbitMQ; 2) a RabbitMQ communication server hosted on the Pi, acting as the central message broker for bi‑directional data and control flow; 3) the controller, a bang‑bang temperature regulator with parameters LL, UL, H, and C, that consumes sensor topics and publishes control commands; 4) a real‑time dashboard that subscribes to broker topics, writes telemetry to a time‑series database, and presents live visualizations; 5) an on‑demand calibration service that invokes a non‑linear least‑squares solver to tune the parameters of Model B during experimental runs; 6) a Kalman filter module that uses the calibrated Model B for anomaly detection and heat‑bed state estimation; 7) a co‑simulation module for what‑if experiments that integrates historical or live PT data with the dynamic models.  All services communicate exclusively via RabbitMQ topics, enabling modular scaling while maintaining tight coupling for rapid feedback loops and supporting the self‑adaptation loop (detection → experiment → calibration → re‑control)."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The incubator Digital Twin follows a four‑phase lifecycle. 1) **Design & Model Development** – Physical and cyber subsystems are described (styrofoam box, heatbed, fan, temperaturesensors, Raspberry Pi controller) and two simulation models are built (Model A with four free parameters, Model B with two). 2) **Integration & Calibration** – The models are integrated into the DT framework (low‑level driver, RabbitMQ communication server, Kalman‑filter‑based monitor). During operation on‑demand calibration (Section 3.3) restores model parameters to the best‑fit values. 3) **Monitoring & Adaptation** – Continuous data streams from PT sensors feed the DT; monitors check safety and performance, triggering anomaly detection or controller re‑configuration. 4) **Experiment & Re‑calibration** – When a change in the plant is detected (e.g., a new bucket of water), the DT schedules experiments, gathers new data, recalibrates Model B, and re‑optimises the controller. Transition between stages is managed by the calibration loop that shifts the twin from predictive simulation to monitoring mode and back. No explicit lifecycle governance or management pattern is documented in the provided materials."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is defined by the set of assumptions underlying Model A and Model B: Assumption 1 (uniform internal temperature), Assumption 2 (negligible wall heat accumulation), Assumption 3 (constant air specific heat), and Assumption 4 (complete conversion of electrical power to air heating). Model B removes Assumption 4, adding a parameter that captures the heatbed’s thermal inertia. Calibration is performed online by estimating the free parameters via a least‑squares or similar optimisation routine whenever new data are collected. Validation and verification rely on co‑simulation between the DT and the real incubator, what‑if simulation scenarios, and Kalman‑filter‑based anomaly detection that flags deviations from expected temperature trajectories. Uncertainty quantification is implicit in the Kalman filter’s covariance; error detection is realised through monitor violations of safety bounds and drift detection. Corrective actions include re‑calibration, controller re‑configuration, and controller parameter optimisation. Quality assurance rests on periodic sensor validation, safety‑protocol enforcement by the low‑level driver, and the ability to replay historical data for model‑dataset consistency checks."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
